---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="PPP — Precise Point Positioning">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/positioning">Positioning</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>PPP</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Positioning · Article 4 of 5</span>
        <h1>PPP — Precise Point Positioning</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Precise Point Positioning achieves decimetre to centimetre accuracy using a single receiver
          anywhere in the world — no local base station required. Instead of differencing with a nearby
          reference, PPP models every error source explicitly using precise satellite orbit and clock
          products computed from a global network of tracking stations.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>12 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#concept">The PPP concept</a></li>
          <li><a href="#observation-model">PPP observation model</a></li>
          <li><a href="#products">Precise orbit and clock products</a></li>
          <li><a href="#convergence">Convergence — the main limitation</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ppp-ar">PPP with ambiguity resolution</a></li>
          <li><a href="#services">Free PPP services</a></li>
          <li><a href="#rtk-vs-ppp">RTK vs PPP — when to use which</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="concept">The PPP concept</h2>
      <p>
        RTK works by differencing observations between a rover and a nearby base station —
        spatially correlated errors cancel. PPP takes the opposite approach: rather than cancelling
        errors by differencing, it <strong>models and corrects every error individually</strong>
        using the most accurate information available.
      </p>

      <div class="concept-compare">
        <div class="concept-col">
          <div class="concept-title">RTK approach</div>
          <div class="concept-method">Error cancellation</div>
          <div class="concept-how">
            Reference station nearby → difference observations → shared errors cancel automatically.
            Fast convergence. Requires local infrastructure.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-divider">vs</div>
        <div class="concept-col">
          <div class="concept-title">PPP approach</div>
          <div class="concept-method">Error modelling</div>
          <div class="concept-how">
            Precise satellite products from global network → model every error term explicitly.
            Slow convergence. Works anywhere on Earth with no local infrastructure.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        For PPP to work, the errors that RTK cancels by differencing must instead be modelled
        with sufficient accuracy. The dominant contributors are:
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Error source</th>
              <th>Broadcast accuracy</th>
              <th>Precise product accuracy</th>
              <th>PPP requirement</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Satellite orbit (radial)</td>
              <td>~1 m</td>
              <td>~2.5 cm (IGS final)</td>
              <td>≤ 5 cm to achieve dm accuracy</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Satellite clock</td>
              <td>~1 m (0.5–2 m)</td>
              <td>~75 ps (~2 cm)</td>
              <td>≤ 1 ns (~30 cm) for dm; ≤ 0.1 ns (~3 cm) for cm</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Ionospheric delay</td>
              <td>~3 m (Klobuchar ~50%)</td>
              <td>Eliminated by dual-freq</td>
              <td>Dual-frequency mandatory for cm PPP</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Tropospheric delay (wet)</td>
              <td>~0.2 m residual</td>
              <td>Estimated in filter</td>
              <td>Estimated simultaneously with position</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Phase wind-up</td>
              <td>Not modelled</td>
              <td>Corrected analytically</td>
              <td>Must correct for sub-cm PPP</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Solid Earth tides</td>
              <td>Not modelled</td>
              <td>Corrected (IERS conventions)</td>
              <td>Up to 0.3 m vertical — must correct</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="observation-model">PPP observation model</h2>
      <p>
        PPP uses undifferenced carrier phase and pseudorange observations from a single receiver.
        After applying precise orbit, clock and deterministic model corrections, the linearised
        observation equations are:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">P_IF = ρ + c·δt_r − c·δt^s + T + ε_P</div>
        <div class="formula">Φ_IF = ρ + c·δt_r − c·δt^s + T + λ_IF·N_IF + ε_Φ</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          P_IF = ionosphere-free code pseudorange (m), Φ_IF = ionosphere-free carrier phase (m),
          ρ = geometric range corrected for satellite orbit, phase wind-up, solid Earth tides,
          relativistic effects (m), c·δt_r = receiver clock error (m), c·δt^s = satellite clock
          error from precise products (m), T = tropospheric delay (estimated in filter),
          N_IF = ionosphere-free float ambiguity (m), ε = observation noise.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The unknowns estimated in the PPP filter are:
      </p>

      <div class="unknowns-ppp">
        <div class="unk-card">
          <div class="unk-sym">Δx, Δy, Δz</div>
          <div class="unk-name">Position increment</div>
          <div class="unk-note">3D position correction from a priori</div>
        </div>
        <div class="unk-card">
          <div class="unk-sym">c·δt_r</div>
          <div class="unk-name">Receiver clock</div>
          <div class="unk-note">Usually modelled as white noise — reset each epoch</div>
        </div>
        <div class="unk-card">
          <div class="unk-sym">ZWD</div>
          <div class="unk-name">Zenith wet delay</div>
          <div class="unk-note">Tropospheric wet component — estimated as random walk</div>
        </div>
        <div class="unk-card unk-ambiguity">
          <div class="unk-sym">N_IF^i</div>
          <div class="unk-name">Float ambiguity</div>
          <div class="unk-note">One per satellite — converges slowly as a real-valued parameter</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The ambiguities in standard PPP are <strong>real-valued</strong> (float), not integers.
        Because there is no differencing, the integer property of the ambiguity is absorbed into
        satellite and receiver hardware biases (uncalibrated phase delays). This is why standard
        PPP requires a long convergence period — it must estimate many parameters simultaneously
        from scratch.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="products">Precise orbit and clock products</h2>
      <p>
        PPP accuracy is directly limited by the accuracy of the satellite orbit and clock products
        it uses. The <strong>International GNSS Service (IGS)</strong> — a voluntary federation of
        more than 400 GNSS tracking stations — produces the world's most accurate publicly available
        products:
      </p>

      <div class="products-table">
        <div class="prod-row prod-header">
          <span>Product</span>
          <span>Orbit accuracy</span>
          <span>Clock accuracy</span>
          <span>Latency</span>
          <span>Use case</span>
        </div>
        <div class="prod-row">
          <span><strong>Broadcast</strong></span>
          <span class="bad">~1 m</span>
          <span class="bad">~1 m</span>
          <span class="good">Real-time</span>
          <span>Standalone GNSS</span>
        </div>
        <div class="prod-row">
          <span><strong>IGS Ultra-rapid</strong></span>
          <span class="warn">~5 cm</span>
          <span class="warn">~150 ps</span>
          <span class="good">Real-time (predicted half)</span>
          <span>Real-time PPP</span>
        </div>
        <div class="prod-row">
          <span><strong>IGS Rapid</strong></span>
          <span class="ok">~2.5 cm</span>
          <span class="ok">~75 ps</span>
          <span class="warn">17 – 41 hours</span>
          <span>Near-real-time PPP</span>
        </div>
        <div class="prod-row">
          <span><strong>IGS Final</strong></span>
          <span class="good">~2.5 cm</span>
          <span class="good">~75 ps</span>
          <span class="bad">12 – 18 days</span>
          <span>Post-processing</span>
        </div>
        <div class="prod-row">
          <span><strong>CNES/CLS (RT)</strong></span>
          <span class="ok">~3 cm</span>
          <span class="ok">~100 ps</span>
          <span class="good">Real-time</span>
          <span>PPP-AR, PPP-RTK</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🌐</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Real-time precise products:</strong> For real-time PPP, precise orbit and clock
          corrections are broadcast via the <strong>IGS State Space Representation (SSR)</strong>
          service over the internet (NTRIP) or satellite (L-band correction services).
          Commercial services — Trimble RTX, Galileo HAS, TerraStar — use the same principle
          but with proprietary correction streams tuned for fast convergence and high reliability.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="convergence">Convergence — the main limitation</h2>
      <p>
        The most significant practical limitation of PPP is <strong>convergence time</strong> —
        the period after initialisation before the solution reaches its full accuracy. Unlike RTK,
        which can achieve centimetre accuracy in seconds after a fixed ambiguity, PPP typically
        requires <strong>20–40 minutes</strong> to converge to decimetre accuracy and
        <strong>1–3 hours</strong> for centimetre accuracy.
      </p>

      <!-- Convergence chart -->
      <div class="convergence-chart">
        <div class="conv-title">Typical PPP convergence behaviour</div>
        <div class="conv-y-label">Horizontal error</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 580 200" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <!-- Grid lines -->
          <line x1="60" y1="20" x2="560" y2="20" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="60" y1="60" x2="560" y2="60" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="60" y1="100" x2="560" y2="100" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="60" y1="140" x2="560" y2="140" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="60" y1="170" x2="560" y2="170" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <!-- Y axis labels -->
          <text x="52" y="24" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">1 m</text>
          <text x="52" y="64" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">50 cm</text>
          <text x="52" y="104" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">20 cm</text>
          <text x="52" y="144" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">10 cm</text>
          <text x="52" y="174" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">5 cm</text>
          <!-- X axis labels -->
          <text x="60"  y="188" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">0</text>
          <text x="160" y="188" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">10 min</text>
          <text x="260" y="188" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">20 min</text>
          <text x="360" y="188" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">40 min</text>
          <text x="460" y="188" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">60 min</text>
          <text x="560" y="188" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">90 min</text>
          <!-- PPP float convergence curve -->
          <path d="M60,22 C80,22 100,28 130,50 C160,72 180,90 220,110 C260,128 300,142 360,158 C420,166 480,170 560,172"
            fill="none" stroke="#fbbf24" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.8"/>
          <!-- PPP-AR convergence curve -->
          <path d="M60,22 C80,22 100,30 130,55 C160,78 190,100 230,115 C280,128 360,155 440,165 C500,170 540,172 560,173"
            fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.8"/>
          <!-- RTK reference line -->
          <line x1="60" y1="172" x2="560" y2="172" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="6 3"/>
          <!-- Legend -->
          <rect x="380" y="28" width="12" height="3" fill="#fbbf24" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="396" y="34" font-size="10" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--sans)">PPP float</text>
          <rect x="380" y="46" width="12" height="3" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="396" y="52" font-size="10" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--sans)">PPP-AR</text>
          <line x1="380" y1="65" x2="392" y2="65" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4 2"/>
          <text x="396" y="68" font-size="10" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--sans)">RTK (reference)</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <p>
        Convergence is slow because the PPP filter must simultaneously estimate position,
        receiver clock, wet tropospheric delay and one float ambiguity per satellite — all
        from scratch. As observations accumulate, the ambiguity estimates improve and the
        position converges.
      </p>

      <p>
        Convergence is faster when:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>More satellites are tracked (multi-constellation)</li>
        <li>More frequencies are available (dual or triple-frequency)</li>
        <li>Precise real-time clock corrections are available with low latency</li>
        <li>Ionospheric conditions are stable (low Kp, no scintillation)</li>
        <li>A good a priori tropospheric model is used</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Re-convergence after outage:</strong> If the receiver loses satellite lock
          (tunnel, building), the ambiguities must be re-estimated from scratch. A 10-second
          outage causes a re-convergence period of several minutes. This is PPP's most
          significant practical disadvantage for kinematic applications compared to RTK.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="ppp-ar">PPP with ambiguity resolution</h2>
      <p>
        Standard PPP estimates ambiguities as real numbers (float). The improvement from
        <strong>PPP-AR</strong> (PPP with Ambiguity Resolution) comes from fixing these to
        integers — just as RTK does — which tightens the position solution and accelerates
        convergence.
      </p>
      <p>
        The challenge is that in undifferenced PPP, the integer property of the ambiguity is
        corrupted by satellite and receiver hardware phase biases (uncalibrated phase delays,
        UPDs). To recover integer ambiguities, the correction service must also estimate and
        broadcast satellite UPDs (also called phase biases or clock biases in narrow-lane form).
      </p>

      <p>
        With satellite UPD corrections applied, the ambiguities recover their integer nature
        and can be fixed using standard LAMBDA. PPP-AR benefits:
      </p>

      <div class="benefit-grid">
        <div class="benefit-card">
          <div class="ben-val">2–3×</div>
          <div class="ben-label">Faster convergence</div>
          <div class="ben-desc">Fixing ambiguities accelerates position convergence from 30+ min to 10–20 min.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="benefit-card">
          <div class="ben-val">1–3 cm</div>
          <div class="ben-label">Horizontal accuracy</div>
          <div class="ben-desc">After convergence with fixed ambiguities. Comparable to RTK in steady-state.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="benefit-card">
          <div class="ben-val">Global</div>
          <div class="ben-label">Coverage</div>
          <div class="ben-desc">No local base station. Works anywhere with a clear sky view and internet/satellite connection for corrections.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="services">Free PPP services</h2>
      <p>
        Several free PPP correction services are available, the most significant being
        <strong>Galileo High Accuracy Service (HAS)</strong>:
      </p>

      <div class="service-cards">
        <div class="service-card service-flagship">
          <div class="svc-name">Galileo HAS</div>
          <div class="svc-badge">Free · Global</div>
          <div class="svc-desc">
            Broadcast free of charge via Galileo E6-B signal. No internet connection required —
            corrections are in the satellite signal itself. Covers GPS and Galileo satellites.
            Horizontal accuracy ~20 cm after convergence. Available globally to any receiver
            with an E6-capable antenna.
          </div>
          <div class="svc-specs">
            <span>Signal: Galileo E6-B (1278.75 MHz)</span>
            <span>Format: HAS ICD</span>
            <span>Accuracy: ~20 cm H (95%)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="service-card">
          <div class="svc-name">CNES PPP-Wizard</div>
          <div class="svc-badge">Free · Research</div>
          <div class="svc-desc">
            Open-source PPP-AR software from CNES. Uses IGS real-time clock and phase bias products.
            Centimetre accuracy after convergence. Primarily used for research and validation.
          </div>
          <div class="svc-specs">
            <span>Delivery: NTRIP</span>
            <span>Format: RTCM SSR</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="service-card">
          <div class="svc-name">NRCan CSRS-PPP</div>
          <div class="svc-badge">Free · Post-processing</div>
          <div class="svc-desc">
            Natural Resources Canada online post-processing service. Submit a RINEX file,
            receive a PPP solution with centimetre accuracy using IGS final products.
            No hardware cost. Ideal for geodetic control surveys.
          </div>
          <div class="svc-specs">
            <span>Delivery: Web upload</span>
            <span>Latency: Minutes</span>
            <span>Accuracy: ~2 cm H</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="rtk-vs-ppp">RTK vs PPP — when to use which</h2>

      <div class="comparison-table">
        <div class="comp-row comp-header">
          <span></span>
          <span>RTK</span>
          <span>PPP</span>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-row">
          <span class="comp-factor">Accuracy (converged)</span>
          <span class="good">1 – 3 cm</span>
          <span class="ok">5 – 20 cm (float) · 1–3 cm (AR)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-row">
          <span class="comp-factor">Time to accuracy</span>
          <span class="good">Seconds (fixed)</span>
          <span class="bad">20 – 60 min (float) · 10 – 20 min (AR)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-row">
          <span class="comp-factor">Infrastructure</span>
          <span class="warn">Base station or CORS network</span>
          <span class="good">None (or internet/satellite for RT)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-row">
          <span class="comp-factor">Coverage</span>
          <span class="warn">Regional (CORS dependent)</span>
          <span class="good">Global</span>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-row">
          <span class="comp-factor">After signal outage</span>
          <span class="good">Re-initialises quickly</span>
          <span class="bad">Full re-convergence</span>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-row">
          <span class="comp-factor">Cost</span>
          <span class="warn">CORS subscription or own base</span>
          <span class="good">Free (Galileo HAS, CSRS-PPP)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-row">
          <span class="comp-factor">Best for</span>
          <span>Survey, machine control, RTK agriculture</span>
          <span>Remote areas, offshore, airborne</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌍</div>
          <div class="summary-title">No base station needed</div>
          <div class="summary-body">PPP uses precise global satellite products instead of a local reference. Works anywhere on Earth — offshore, airborne, remote wilderness.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⏳</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Convergence is the cost</div>
          <div class="summary-body">20–60 minutes to decimetres, 1–3 hours to centimetres for float PPP. Re-convergence after outages. This is the fundamental trade-off vs RTK.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🎯</div>
          <div class="summary-title">PPP-AR accelerates convergence</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Satellite phase bias corrections allow integer ambiguity fixing. Cuts convergence to 10–20 minutes. Galileo HAS delivers this free globally via E6.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Precise products are key</div>
          <div class="summary-body">IGS orbit and clock products (2.5 cm / 75 ps) are what separate PPP from standalone. Real-time products enable real-time PPP via NTRIP or L-band.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/positioning/rtk" class="nav-prev">← RTK</a>
        <a href="/learn/positioning/ppp-rtk" class="nav-next">PPP-RTK →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Zumberge, J. F., Heflin, M. B., Jefferson, D. C., Watkins, M. M. & Webb, F. H. (1997). Precise point positioning for the efficient and robust analysis of GPS data from large networks. <em>Journal of Geophysical Research</em>, 102(B3), 5005–5017.</li>
          <li>Ge, M., Gendt, G., Rothacher, M., Shi, C. & Liu, J. (2008). Resolution of GPS carrier-phase ambiguities in precise point positioning (PPP) with daily observations. <em>Journal of Geodesy</em>, 82, 389–399.</li>
          <li>Galileo HAS ICD. <a href="https://www.gsc-europa.eu/sites/default/files/sites/all/files/Galileo-HAS-SIS-ICD_v1.0.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GSC Europa →</a></li>
          <li>IGS Products. <a href="https://igs.org/products/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">igs.org/products →</a></li>
          <li>NRCan CSRS-PPP. <a href="https://webapp.csrs-scrs.nrcan-rncan.gc.ca/geod/tools-outils/ppp.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NRCan →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
